Project Objective:¶

Build a predictive model to estimate user activity two weeks in advance based on behavioral data (e.g., total answers, new contacts, active days), with the goal of identifying users at risk of churn and improving retention strategies.

In [82]:
def clean_and_convert_types(df: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    Cleans the dataframe by:
    - Replacing 'NULL' and '#VALUE!' with None
    - Converting datetime-like strings to datetime using '%d/%m/%Y %H:%M' only when conversion is likely,
      excluding specific columns explicitly
    - Converting all remaining object-type columns to string to fix mixed types

    Args:
        df (pd.DataFrame): Input DataFrame

    Returns:
        pd.DataFrame: Cleaned DataFrame
    """
    # Replace invalid markers
    df = df.replace({"NULL": None, "#VALUE!": None})

    # Manually converted columns (case-sensitive as per DataFrame column names)
    convert_to_str = {  # patch
        "ProfileStatusText",
        "AppVersion",
        "DeleteReason",
        "DeviceId",
    }
    convert_to_int = {  # patch
        "UserIdMin",
        "UserIdMin",
    }

    for col in df.select_dtypes(include="object").columns:
        if col in convert_to_str:
            df[col] = df[col].astype(str)
            continue

        if col in convert_to_int:
            df[col] = df[col].astype(int)
            continue

        # Sample to test if the column is likely datetime
        sample = (
            df[col]
            .dropna()
            .astype(str)
            .sample(n=min(100, len(df[col].dropna())), random_state=42)
        )
        parsed = pd.to_datetime(sample, format="%d/%m/%Y %H:%M", errors="coerce")
        success_rate = parsed.notnull().mean()

        if success_rate >= 0.8:
            df[col] = pd.to_datetime(df[col], format="%d/%m/%Y %H:%M", errors="coerce")
        else:
            df[col] = df[col].astype(str)

    return df

def is_identifier_or_datetime(colname: str) -> bool:
    col_lower = colname.lower()
    return (
        col_lower == "id"
        or colname.endswith("Id")
        or colname.endswith("ID")
        or "date" in col_lower
        or "time" in col_lower
    )


def interactive_eda(df: pd.DataFrame) -> None:
    """
    Perform a fully Bokeh-based interactive EDA on the provided DataFrame,
    excluding datetime, identifier, and 100% missing columns from plots/statistics.
    """
    print("★ DataFrame Shape:", df.shape)
    print("★ Columns:", list(df.columns))
    print("★ Data Types:")
    print(df.dtypes)

    # --- Describe Statistics ---
    display(df.describe(include="all"))

    # --- Missing Values ---
    print("\n★ Missing Values:")
    missing_count = df.isnull().sum()
    missing_percent = (missing_count / len(df)) * 100
    missing_summary = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Missing Count": missing_count, "Missing %": missing_percent.round(2)}
    )
    display(
        missing_summary[missing_summary["Missing Count"] > 0].sort_values(
            "Missing %", ascending=False
        )
    )

    # --- Remove columns with 100% missing values ---
    df = df.loc[:, df.notnull().any()]

    # --- Select Clean Numerical Features ---
    numerical_features = [
        col
        for col in df.select_dtypes(include=["int64", "float64"]).columns
        if not is_identifier_or_datetime(col)
    ]

    # --- Distribution Histograms ---
    if numerical_features:
        histograms = []
        for col in numerical_features:
            hist, edges = np.histogram(df[col].dropna(), bins=30)
            p = figure(
                title=f"Distribution of {col}",
                background_fill_color="#fafafa",
                width=400,
                height=300,
            )
            p.quad(
                top=hist,
                bottom=0,
                left=edges[:-1],
                right=edges[1:],
                fill_color="navy",
                line_color="white",
                alpha=0.7,
            )
            p.xaxis.axis_label = col
            p.yaxis.axis_label = "Frequency"
            histograms.append(p)
        show(gridplot(histograms, ncols=2))
    else:
        print("\n★ No suitable numerical features for histograms.")

    # --- Boxplots ---
    if numerical_features:
        boxplots = []
        for col in numerical_features:
            q1, q2, q3 = df[col].quantile([0.25, 0.5, 0.75])
            iqr = q3 - q1
            lower = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
            upper = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
            source = ColumnDataSource(
                data=dict(
                    x=[col], q1=[q1], q2=[q2], q3=[q3], lower=[lower], upper=[upper]
                )
            )
            p = figure(title=f"Boxplot of {col}", width=400, height=300, x_range=[col])
            p.vbar(
                x="x",
                width=0.7,
                top="q3",
                bottom="q2",
                source=source,
                fill_color="#E08E79",
            )
            p.vbar(
                x="x",
                width=0.7,
                top="q2",
                bottom="q1",
                source=source,
                fill_color="#3B8686",
            )
            p.segment("x", "upper", "x", "q3", source=source)
            p.segment("x", "lower", "x", "q1", source=source)
            boxplots.append(p)
        show(gridplot(boxplots, ncols=2))
    else:
        print("\n★ No suitable numerical features for boxplots.")

    # --- Categorical Distributions ---
    categorical_features = df.select_dtypes(include=["object"]).columns.tolist()
    categorical_features = [
        col for col in categorical_features if df[col].notnull().sum() > 0
    ]
    if categorical_features:
        barplots = []
        for col in categorical_features:
            top_categories = df[col].value_counts(normalize=True).head(10)
            category_labels = top_categories.index.astype(
                str
            ).tolist()  # ✅ Convert to string
            source = ColumnDataSource(
                data=dict(
                    categories=category_labels,
                    counts=top_categories.values.tolist(),
                )
            )
            p = figure(
                x_range=category_labels,
                title=f"Top categories in {col}",
                width=400,
                height=300,
            )
            p.vbar(
                x="categories",
                top="counts",
                width=0.9,
                source=source,
                line_color="white",
                fill_color=factor_cmap(
                    "categories",
                    palette=Spectral10,
                    factors=category_labels,
                ),
            )
            p.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 1
            p.xaxis.axis_label = col
            p.yaxis.axis_label = "Proportion"
            barplots.append(p)
        show(gridplot(barplots, ncols=2))
    else:
        print("\n★ No categorical features for barplots.")

    # --- Correlation Heatmap ---
    if len(numerical_features) >= 2:
        corr = df[numerical_features].corr().stack().reset_index()
        corr.columns = ["Feature1", "Feature2", "Correlation"]
        corr = corr[corr["Feature1"] != corr["Feature2"]]
        source = ColumnDataSource(corr)
        mapper = LinearColorMapper(palette=Spectral10, low=-1.0, high=1.0)
        p = figure(
            x_range=numerical_features,
            y_range=numerical_features,
            width=800,
            height=800,
            title="Correlation Heatmap with ColorBar",
            toolbar_location=None,
            tools="",
        )
        p.rect(
            x="Feature1",
            y="Feature2",
            width=1,
            height=1,
            source=source,
            line_color=None,
            fill_alpha=0.8,
            fill_color={"field": "Correlation", "transform": mapper},
        )
        color_bar = ColorBar(
            color_mapper=mapper,
            ticker=BasicTicker(desired_num_ticks=len(Spectral10)),
            label_standoff=12,
            border_line_color=None,
            location=(0, 0),
        )
        p.add_layout(color_bar, "right")
        show(p)
    else:
        print("\n★ Not enough numerical features for correlation heatmap.")

Features Engineering¶

Created behavioral features such as total answers, number of new contacts, and active days.

Applied normalization, handled missing values, and selected key features based on importance and correlation with future user activity.

Aggregated interactions over time windows to reflect recent engagement.

Extract All Users History¶

Aggregated each user's full interaction history by combining session and message data.

For every user, constructed timelines of past behavior including session states, message types, activity and engagement levels.

This user-level history serves as the foundation for generating personalized features across different 2-weeks time periods.

In [90]:
def extract_all_users_history(
    df_activity: pd.DataFrame,
    df_messages: pd.DataFrame,
    df_sessions: pd.DataFrame,
    df_users: pd.DataFrame,
) -> list[dict]:
    """
    Builds a list of user activity profiles with all relevant data sorted by time,
    and extracts static features and 14-day date-based windows for each user using .date().

    Returns:
        list[dict]: A list of user profiles with static and dynamic features.
    """
    all_users = []
    static_features = [
        "AllowNewConnectionPush",
        "AllowNewMessagePush",
        "AllowNotificationFromConnections",
        "AllowNotificationFromMatchs",
    ]

    all_user_ids = df_activity["UserId"].unique()

    for user_id in all_user_ids:
        user_activity = df_activity[df_activity["UserId"] == user_id].copy()
        user_messages = df_messages[df_messages["UserId"] == user_id].copy()

        user_sessions = df_sessions[
            (df_sessions["UserIdMin"] == user_id)
            | (df_sessions["UserIdMax"] == user_id)
        ].copy()

        user_info = df_users[df_users["UserId"] == user_id].copy()

        if "Date" in user_activity.columns:
            user_activity["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(user_activity["Date"]).dt.date
            user_activity = user_activity.sort_values(by="Date")

        if "CreatedAt" in user_messages.columns:
            user_messages["CreatedAt"] = pd.to_datetime(
                user_messages["CreatedAt"]
            ).dt.date
            user_messages = user_messages.sort_values(by="CreatedAt")

        if "CreatedAt" in user_sessions.columns:
            user_sessions["CreatedAt"] = pd.to_datetime(
                user_sessions["CreatedAt"]
            ).dt.date
            user_sessions = user_sessions.sort_values(by="CreatedAt")

        if "LastActiveDate" in user_info.columns:
            user_info["LastActiveDate"] = pd.to_datetime(
                user_info["LastActiveDate"]
            ).dt.date
            user_info = user_info.sort_values(by="LastActiveDate")

        # Extract date boundaries from sessions
        if not user_sessions.empty:
            start_date = user_sessions["CreatedAt"].min()
            last_date = user_sessions["CreatedAt"].max()
        else:
            start_date = None
            last_date = None

        # Generate 14-day date-only windows
        dynamic_features = []
        if start_date and last_date:
            current = start_date
            while current <= last_date:
                from_date = current
                to_date = min(current + timedelta(days=13), last_date)

                dynamic_features.append(
                    {"UserId": user_id, "FromDate": from_date, "ToDate": to_date}
                )

                current = to_date + timedelta(days=1)

        user_history = {
            "UserId": user_id,
            "StartDate": start_date,
            "LastDate": last_date,
            "activity": user_activity,
            "messages": user_messages,
            "sessions": user_sessions,
            "user_info": user_info,
            "static_features": (
                user_info[static_features]
                if not user_info.empty
                else pd.DataFrame(columns=static_features)
            ),
            "dynamic_features": pd.DataFrame(dynamic_features),
        }

        all_users.append(user_history)

    return all_users

Compute Dynamic Features¶

Calculated dynamic, time-windowed features that reflect users' recent behavioral changes.

These include rolling counts of answers, new contacts, active days, session transitions, and message activity.

By capturing trends and momentum in user behavior, these features help the model detect early signals of churn or sustained engagement.

In [92]:
def compute_dynamic_features(all_users_history: list[dict]) -> list[dict]:
    """
    Calculates dynamic features for each user in all_users_history, for every 14-day window.

    Args:
        all_users_history (list[dict]): Output from extract_all_users_history.

    Returns:
        list[dict]: Updated user history with enriched dynamic_features.
    """
    enriched_users_history = []

    for user in all_users_history:
        user_id = user["UserId"]
        activity = user["activity"]
        messages = user["messages"]
        sessions = user["sessions"]
        user_info = user["user_info"]
        dynamic_features = user["dynamic_features"]

        birthdate = pd.to_datetime(user_info["BirthDate"].iloc[0], errors="coerce")
        all_periods = []  # 14-days windows
        all_contacts = set()  # contacts of the user before the current period

        for _, row in dynamic_features.iterrows():
            from_date = row["FromDate"]
            to_date = row["ToDate"]

            # Number of active days
            num_active_days = activity[
                (activity["Date"] >= from_date) & (activity["Date"] <= to_date)
            ]["Date"].nunique()

            # Session filtering
            session_window = sessions[
                (sessions["CreatedAt"] >= from_date)
                & (sessions["CreatedAt"] <= to_date)
            ]

            # User Age from BirthDate
            user_age = (
                # convert a date object into a full datetime object with the time set to midnight (00:00:00).
                datetime.combine(from_date, datetime.min.time())
                - birthdate
            ).days // 365  # in years

            total_sessions = len(session_window)

            # Unique new connections (new UserIds from Min/Max)
            total_in_min = session_window["UserIdMin"].dropna().unique().tolist()
            total_in_max = session_window["UserIdMax"].dropna().unique().tolist()
            current_contacts = set(total_in_min + total_in_max)

            # Only include those not seen before
            # all_contacts are the contacts of the user before the current period
            new_contacts = current_contacts - all_contacts
            num_new_contacts = len(new_contacts)
            # Update the set with new contacts for cumulative tracking
            all_contacts.update(new_contacts)
            num_all_contacts = len(all_contacts)

            # Histogram of States
            state_histogram = session_window["State"].value_counts().to_dict()
            for i in range(1, 8):
                state_histogram.setdefault(i, 0)

            # Status: 1 if all sessions in window are State==1 else -1 (deleted)
            status = (
                1
                if (not session_window.empty and session_window["State"].eq(1).all())
                else -1
            )

            # Message filtering
            messages_window = messages[
                (messages["CreatedAt"] >= from_date)
                & (messages["CreatedAt"] <= to_date)
            ]

            # User was active if they sent a message or answered
            was_active = int(not messages_window.empty)

            # Message and answer counts
            total_questions = messages_window["QuestionId"].dropna().nunique()
            total_answers = messages_window["AnswerId"].dropna().nunique()
            total_messages = total_questions + total_answers
            question_answer_gap = total_questions - total_answers

            # Histogram of Messages Type
            type_histogram = messages_window["type"].value_counts().to_dict()
            for i in range(1, 4):
                type_histogram.setdefault(i, 0)

            n_min = len(total_in_min)
            n_max = len(total_in_max)

            period_features = {
                "UserId": user_id,
                "FromDate": from_date,
                "ToDate": to_date,
                "UserAge": user_age,
                "NumActiveDays": num_active_days,
                "NumNewContacts": num_new_contacts,
                "NumAllContacts": num_all_contacts,
                "TotalQuestions": total_questions,
                "TotalAnswers": total_answers,
                "TotalMessages": total_messages,
                "QA_gap": question_answer_gap,
                "Status": status,
                "WasActive": was_active,
                "TotalInMin": n_min,
                "TotalInMax": n_max,
                "DelTotalInMinMax": n_min - n_max,
                "TotalSessions": total_sessions,
            }

            # Add state histogram values (State_1 through State_7)
            for state in range(1, 8):
                period_features[f"State_{state}"] = state_histogram[state]

            # Add messages type histogram values (MsgType_1 through MsgType_3)
            for type_ in range(1, 4):
                period_features[f"MsgType_{type_}"] = type_histogram[type_]

            # Target Variables: will be calculated later as sum of quantiles from entire population
            period_features["ActivityScore"] = np.nan
            period_features["InactivityScore"] = np.nan
            period_features["Churn"] = 1 - was_active

            all_periods.append(period_features)
        # end for 14-days periods

        user["dynamic_features"] = pd.DataFrame(all_periods)
        enriched_users_history.append(user)
    # end for users

    return enriched_users_history

Generate Features Table¶

Combine Static and Dynamic Features into single DataFrame;¶

Merged long-term user attributes (static features) with short-term behavior patterns (dynamic features) into a unified DataFrame.

This consolidated dataset provides a comprehensive view of each user’s profile and recent activity, enabling more accurate churn prediction.

In [94]:
def generate_features_table(all_users_history: list[dict]) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    Merges static and dynamic features for all users into a single DataFrame.

    Each user's static features are replicated for every 14-day window (dynamic row),
    and combined side-by-side.

    Args:
        all_users_history (list[dict]): List of user dictionaries, each containing:
            - 'static_features': DataFrame with a single row
            - 'dynamic_features': DataFrame with multiple time-windowed rows

    Returns:
        pd.DataFrame: Final dataset with merged static and dynamic features.
    """

    all_rows = []
    for user in all_users_history:
        dynamic_df = user.get("dynamic_features", pd.DataFrame())
        static_df = user.get("static_features", pd.DataFrame())

        if dynamic_df.empty or static_df.empty:
            continue

        # Get the only row from static_features and replicate it
        static_row = static_df.iloc[0]
        repeated_static = pd.DataFrame([static_row] * len(dynamic_df))

        # Combine side-by-side
        combined = pd.concat(
            [
                repeated_static.reset_index(drop=True),
                dynamic_df.reset_index(drop=True),
            ],
            axis=1,
        )
        all_rows.append(combined)
    # end for users
    # Return combined dataset
    return pd.concat(all_rows, ignore_index=True)


def inplace_quantile_normalization(df: pd.DataFrame, columns: list[str]) -> None:
    """
    Perform quantile normalization on selected columns and replace values in-place.

    Args:
        df (pd.DataFrame): Input DataFrame to be modified.
        columns (list[str]): Columns to normalize in-place.
    """
    for col in columns:
        if col in df.columns:
            series = df[col].dropna()
            df[col] = df[col].apply(
                lambda x: (
                    percentileofscore(series, x, kind="mean") / 100
                    if pd.notna(x)
                    else None
                )
            )

Create Target Prediction Variable¶

To predict the ActivityScore from the end of the current week to the next 2 weeks, we essentially modeling how active a user will be in the upcoming 14 days, based on their behavior up until now (end of this week).

Can we predict next-period activity based on current behavior?

In [99]:
def remove_shift_artifacts(
    df: pd.DataFrame, user_col: str, shift_n: int
) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    Removes rows that would cause cross-user data contamination when applying shift().
    Assumes the DataFrame is sorted by UserID and Date.

    Args:
        df (pd.DataFrame): Input DataFrame, sorted by user and time.
        user_col (str): Column name for user ID.
        shift_n (int): Number of rows to shift (positive or negative).

    Returns:
        pd.DataFrame: Cleaned DataFrame without contaminated shift rows.
    """
    df = df.copy()

    # Determine user group for shifted row
    shifted_users = df[user_col].shift(shift_n)

    # Mark contaminated rows — where shifted row would be from a different user
    df["is_dirty_shift"] = df[user_col] != shifted_users

    # Drop contaminated rows
    df = df[~df["is_dirty_shift"]].drop(columns=["is_dirty_shift"])

    return df

⚠️ Attention:

Vertical bands on the left (x ~ 0.1–0.3): Indicates discretization or imbalance in the target variable — many repeated values, possibly due to rounding, grouping, or unnatural inputs.

High variance at low y_test values:
The model struggles to predict inactive users — it tends to overestimate their activity.

Inaccurate regression near zero:
The model predicts nonzero activity even for users who were completely inactive.

Transform to Binary Classification Problem and Plot ROC Curve¶

What we have:

  • y_test and y_pred in the range [0, 1],
  • and we want to evaluate ranking quality (e.g., how well the model distinguishes between active and inactive users),

then we build an ROC curve — but first, we need to define a binary target.

Explanation¶

SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) summary:

  • Which features impact the prediction most

  • How they influence it (positively or negatively).

  • SHAP values show how much a feature pushes the prediction up or down.

Centered around 0:

➕ Right = increase prediction

➖ Left = decrease prediction

  • Red = high feature value

  • Blue = low feature value

Partial Dependence Plots (PDP):

Each subplot shows how changing a single feature value affects the model's average prediction, holding all other features constant.

  • X-axis: feature value (normalized here between 0–1).

  • Y-axis: predicted ActivityScore (partial dependence).

Model Performance Summary¶

  • Model: LightGBM Regressor
  • MAE (Mean Absolute Error): 0.1486
  • R² Score: 0.5192
  • F1-Score: (threshold = 0.2): 0.8664

These metrics indicate a moderate predictive performance, with the model capturing approximately 52% of the variance in churn behavior. The MAE shows that, on average, the prediction error is about 0.15 units.
